entry.title: Make trailing space hanging behavior depend on the item's style
entry.content:
The CL https://crrev.com/c/4881393 changed the hanging space behavior

to not depend on `text-align`, and it updated the implementation to

match the spec text. However, that patch had a misunderstanding of the

spec that made each line's hanging space behavior depend on its block

container's styles, rather than on each space's inline item styles.

That caused incompatibilities with other browsers.



This patch makes this behavior dependent on the inline item styles,

thus fixing the main source of incompatibilities.



The spec text is not yet fully clear on the behavior of some edge

cases, which is why the WPT tests this CL adds are marked as

tentative. See https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/9724 for the

CSSWG issue discussing this.

entry.title: Revert "ozone/drm: Retry test modesets w/ all possible CRTC-connector permutations"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 1846ac9e49f1d034c546fa11534319415a9bbaac.



Reason for revert: Causing failures on the CrOS ASan LSan bot

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Chromium%20OS%20ASan%20LSan%20Tests%20(1)/56734/overview



Original change's description:

> ozone/drm: Retry test modesets w/ all possible CRTC-connector permutations

>

> The kernel sometimes uses multiple CRTCs for a single connector without

> marking the CRTC as in use to userspace. One such case is when

> Bigjoiner (an intel driver feature) takes an additional CRTC for high

> bandwidth modes. Modesetting with a stolen CRTC will result in failure.

> The only way to work around additional CRTCs being taken is to test

> modeset on various CRTC-connector permutations, and to use the

> permutation that doesn’t fail.

>

> This CL adds a fallback logic on test modeset failure.

> The fallback logic generates all possible permutations of

> CRTC-connector pairings given each connectors’ possible CRTCs, and

> tries to test modeset on all of them. The fallback will immediately

> terminate upon the first test modeset success.

>

> Ozone will revert any changes to its abstractions that were made during

> the fallback attempts, such that the original CRTC-connector pairings

> before the configure request are maintained. Maintaining the original

> pairings is necessary as pageflips with old display state might

> interleave the UI's fallback test modesets. GetNativeDisplays()

> attempts to maintain stability of CRTC-connector pairings whenever

> possible, which leads to dramatically decreased chances of pageflip

> failure (which results in GPU process crash).

>

> high-bandwidth display

entry.title: DOM: Implement Observable#from() conversion operator
entry.content:
This CL implements 3/4 of the Observable#from() conversion operator.

This operator [1], [2] (not quite yet specified) takes a Web IDL `any`

value and converts it to an Observable with the following semantics,

based on what the `any` value actually is under the hood:



1. Observable: just return the same Observable.

2. Async iterable: create & return an Observable that, on

subscription, pulls values from the async iterable, and pushes them

to the subscriber.

3. Iterable: create & return an Observable that, on subscription,

synchronously pushes each value to the subscriber.

4. Promise: create & return an Observable that, on subscription,

reacts [3] to given promise with two handlers:

a. Fulfillment handler: pushes the value to the subscriber, and

calls complete()

b. Rejection handler: Calls the subscriber's error with the given

rejection value



This CL implements (1), (3), and (4) by introducing new subscriber

delegates that are specific to these cases. Async iterable support, (2),

will come in a future CL, as there is not yet equivalent bindings

support for this, so it will need a more thoughtful design.



[1]:

https://github.com/wicg/observable?tab=readme-ov-file#constructing--converting-objects-to-observables

[2]: https://wicg.github.io/observable/#observable-from

[3]: https://webidl.spec.whatwg.org/#dfn-perform-steps-once-promise-is-settled



Bug: 40282760

entry.title: Handle snap group windows when synchronizing layer trees
entry.content:
Currently when synchronizing layer trees of WindowMiniView for overview

and alt-tab cases, we assume that both bottom corners of the

WindowMiniView are rounded. However, this is not true when windows are

part of a snap group.



To address this issue, we have introduced a helper method that

finds the radii of WindowMiniView, considering whether the window is

part of a snap group.



This method is used to determine the correct rounded corners against

which the layer trees are synchronized.

entry.title: New toolchain for Windows 11 10.0.22621.2428 SDK
entry.content:
A couple of Chromium projects need access to Windows features that are

only exposed in the 2428 point release of 10.0.22621. The previous

toolchain package used the 10.0.22621.755 (Windows 11 22H2) SDK. This

follows the same packaging steps but it pulls in the latest SDK, thus

giving access to the new features.



When we start depending on the new SDK then developers who don't use the

packaged toolchain will need to update their locally installed SDK. The

changes that add the dependencies on the new SDK will check for it and

give error messages to guide developers.



Packaging was done on a Windows 10 Hyper-V VM, cleanly created for this

purpose. Specifically, the Hyper-V Quick Create tool was used to create

a Windows 11 dev environment. VS Community Edition was then uninstalled.



Then the package was created by installing depot_tools, downloading the

VS Professional 2022 installer from https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/downloads/

(free trial, not preview) and then running the installer like this:



$ PATH_TO_INSTALLER.EXE ^

--add Microsoft.VisualStudio.Workload.NativeDesktop ^

--add Microsoft.VisualStudio.Component.VC.ATLMFC ^

--add Microsoft.VisualStudio.Component.VC.Tools.ARM64 ^

--add Microsoft.VisualStudio.Component.VC.MFC.ARM64 ^

--includeRecommended --passive



Then Add/Remove programs was used to modify the SDK to add the Debuggers

package.



Then the packaging script was run like this:



python3 depot_tools\win_toolchain\package_from_installed.py 2022 -w 10.0.22621.0



The packaging process was done on new VMs hosted on two different

machines to make sure that the results were consistent.



Updates were made to the comments and documentation, however very few

updates were needed because the SDK change is just a point release.
